photo.title: Fidenza - Cattedrale di San Donnino
photo.tags: fidenza duomodifidenza cattedraledisandonnino fidenzacathedral borgosandonnino domninusoffidenza sigerictheserious viafrancigena benedettoantelami antelami barbarossa pallavicino cephalophore kephalophor emiliaromagnaitaly
photo.description:
In 1927, what is pretty recent, the city "Borgo San Donnino" changed it´s name to "Fidenza", as in Roman times it was known as "Fidentia Julia".
The city was named and the Duomo inside the walls was dedicated to San Donnino di Fidenza (aka "Domninus of Fidenza"), who was martyred nearby in 291.
Sigeric the Serious, Archbishop of Canterbury, made the pilgrimage to Rome following the Via Francigena around 990. His contemporary records of this journey still exist (and are source for the modern guide books). He reached "Sce Domnine" after 36 days, what is pretty fast for more than 1000kms.
The erection of the Cattedrale di San Donnino started in the 11th century, the first consecration took place in 1106, though the building process continued. From around 1200 on Master Benedetto Antelami and his workshop worked here, not only as Master masons. Antelami may as well be the architect of the facade.
Frederick Barbarossa had entrusted "Borgo San Donnino" to the Pallavicino family of Piacenza. In 1268 - after a siege - the city was conquered by the troops of Parma, who looted and burnt down it completely. All houses got destroyed at that time just the Duomo was saved, but it was not completed at that time. The building process came to a stop - and was never continued.
Three episodes of life and death of San Donnino are over the central portal. In the center is the beheading of the saint, who after becoming a martyr that way became a kephalophor as well, as he carried away his won head, just like Saint-Denis, Saint Solange and many others.
The archivolt is populated by dwarfs (?).

photo.tags: elsenyordelsbertins canon ixus310hs catalunya cataluña catalonia espanya españa spain barcelonaprovincia moianes moia farinera borda amanitaphalloides bolet seta mushroom fungi farinot cogomella mort muerte death perillos peligroso dangerous perill peligro danger senderisme senderismo hiking gebracb excursiomoiavalldemarfa
photo.description: La farinera borda, farinot o pentinella borda o cogoma borda (Amanita phalloides) és un bolet pudent de l'ordre dels agaricals, que a vegades pot adoptar forma de fal·lus. És altament tòxica, i la responsable de la majoria de morts per la intoxicació en l'ingestió de bolets. Conté dos tipus de toxines: fal·lotoxines i amatoxines. Presenta una coloració típicament verd oliva, brillant amb temps sec, lleugerament viscosa amb humitat. El seu tiny no és sempre uniforme; algunes formes són molt pàlides, inclús blanques. Exhala un lleuger olor a pètals de roses que s'accentua amb l'edat o amb la dessecació. El principal verí que conté és l'amanitina, que actua d'una manera ben destructiva. Poca broma amb els bolets. Excursió a la Vall de Marfà. A Google Maps.

photo.tags: 1835mm d750 florida lowdermilkpark naples nikkor nikon beach longexposure rocks southwestflorida sunset
photo.description: A long exposure (5 seconds) just after sunset near Lowdermilk Park in Naples, Florida. This was one of many exposures, but my earlier attempts weren't so successful. I thought that I could get away without using an ND grad filter. In fact, I don't own an ND grad filter, but I could have tried my hand or the brim of my cap. By the time I took this shot, there was enough balance between the sky and the foreground that the sky wasn't blown out, especially when I combined the normal exposure with one that was under exposed. The resulting HDR was only a mild correction, but probably an improvement over the original exposure. (I hadn't intended to shoot an HDR, but I noticed when I got home that I had two identical frames with different exposures.)
